  "prompt": "What is the difference between Shall and Will?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the differences between \"shall\" and \"will\":\n\nShall:\n1. Traditionally used for first-person (I/we) to express future actions or intentions\n2. More formal and somewhat old-fashioned\n3. Often used in legal or official documents\n4. Can express a strong determination or promise\n5. Used in questions to make suggestions or offers\n\nExamples:\n- I shall be 30 years old next year.\n- Shall we go to dinner?\n\nWill:\n1. Used for all persons (I, you, he/she/it, we, they)\n2. More common in modern English\n3. Expresses simple future actions\n4. Indicates willingness or intention\n5. Used in predictions and spontaneous decisions\n\nExamples:\n- She will arrive tomorrow.\n- I will help you with your homework.\n\nCurrent Usage:\n- In contemporary English, \"will\" is used more frequently\n- \"Shall\" is mostly used in formal or legal contexts\n- In everyday speech, \"will\" is preferred for most future expressions\n\nGenerally, modern English speakers tend to use \"will\" for most future references, regardless of the person.",
